Return-Ready: The Church Christ Is Coming Back For

Written by Vivamus de Silva

Mission Brief

Scripture does not hand us a calendar to flex. It hands us a posture to hold. Jesus didn‚Äôt give Matthew 24‚Äì25 to fuel speculation or feed fear; He gave it to form disciples‚Äîawake, clean, steady, and on mission‚Äîbecause the King is returning and He will not find His people asleep at the wheel (Matthew 24:42; 25:13).

The question isn‚Äôt ‚ÄúCan you predict the hour?‚Äù The question is ‚ÄúAre you faithful in the hour you‚Äôve been given?‚Äù Before the Lord returns, the environment intensifies‚Äîdeception increases, lawlessness multiplies, love chills, endurance gets tested (Matthew 24:10‚Äì13). And in that pressure, Christ is refining a people whose readiness is not performance. It‚Äôs formation.

---

Grace Engine

Readiness is never earned. It is produced.

We are saved by grace, not by grind‚Äî‚Äúnot a result of works‚Äù‚Äîand we are saved for obedience‚Äî‚Äúcreated in Christ Jesus for good works‚Äù (Ephesians 2:8‚Äì10). God didn‚Äôt rescue you so you could run on self-righteous fumes; He rescued you so you could live in the power of the Spirit, bearing fruit that proves the root (Titus 3:5). Grace pardons‚Äîand grace trains (Titus 2:11‚Äì14).

So when Scripture calls the church to watchfulness, holiness, endurance, and mission, it is not demanding payment. It is describing what living union with Christ produces.

---

The Return-Ready Posture

1) Awake: Watchful, Sober, Discerned

Jesus‚Äô command is direct: stay awake (Matthew 24:42). Paul echoes it: ‚ÄúLet us not sleep‚Ä¶ but keep awake and be sober‚Äù (1 Thessalonians 5:6). Watchfulness isn‚Äôt paranoia; it is spiritual clarity in a world engineered for distraction.

A return-ready church tests claims‚Äîprophets, headlines, and trending ‚Äútruths‚Äù‚Äîby the Word of God (1 John 4:1). She does not confuse confidence with accuracy. She does not confuse charisma with holiness. She lives alert because accountability is real.

Berean Protocol: search the Scriptures to verify what you‚Äôre hearing (Acts 17:11).

---

2) Clean: Holy, Repentant, Uncompromised

The New Testament frames the church as a bride preparing for the Bridegroom (Ephesians 5:25‚Äì27; Revelation 19:7‚Äì8). That is not decoration language; that is identity language. Christ is purifying His people‚Äînot polishing a brand.

Peter asks the unavoidable question: ‚ÄúWhat sort of people ought you to be‚Ä¶ in lives of holiness and godliness?‚Äù (2 Peter 3:11). John makes it operational: ‚ÄúEveryone who thus hopes in Him purifies himself as He is pure‚Äù (1 John 3:3).

Clean does not mean sinless perfection. Clean means quick repentance, honest confession, and real separation from what defiles. The return-ready church does not rename sin to keep peace. She kills it to keep faith.

Confession Protocol: ‚ÄúIf we confess our sins‚Ä¶ He is faithful and just to forgive‚Äù (1 John 1:9).

---

3) Courageous: Endurance Under Fire

Jesus promised trouble‚Äîand victory inside it: ‚ÄúIn the world you will have tribulation. But take heart; I have overcome the world‚Äù (John 16:33). Endurance is not optional in the last stretch: ‚ÄúThe one who endures to the end will be saved‚Äù (Matthew 24:13).

Revelation shows how believers overcome: ‚Äúby the blood of the Lamb and by the word of their testimony‚Ä¶ even unto death‚Äù (Revelation 12:11). This is not image management. This is faithful witness under pressure.

The return-ready church does not fold when obedience gets expensive. She stands, not because she is strong in herself, but because Christ is strong in her.

Obedience Protocol: don‚Äôt be a hearer only‚Äîbe a doer (James 1:22).

---

4) Mission-Locked: Gospel First, Always

Jesus ties the end to the mission: ‚ÄúThis gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed‚Ä¶ and then the end will come‚Äù (Matthew 24:14). Right before His ascension, He didn‚Äôt give a survival kit‚ÄîHe gave a commission (Matthew 28:18‚Äì20). The Spirit empowers witness, not retreat (Acts 1:8).

A return-ready church is not entertained into maturity. She is mobilized into witness. She remembers why she exists: proclaim Christ crucified and risen, call sinners to repentance and faith, and make disciples who obey Jesus.

Mission Protocol: share the gospel; build disciples‚Äîrepeat.

---

5) Anchored: Apostolic Doctrine in an Age of Counterfeits

Deception is a last-days reality (Matthew 24:4‚Äì5, 11). Paul warns that many will prefer teachers who scratch their desires rather than submit to truth (2 Timothy 4:3‚Äì4). That means the pressure isn‚Äôt only open rebellion; it‚Äôs religious imitation.

A return-ready church remains devoted to the apostolic teaching (Acts 2:42). She does not ‚Äúupdate‚Äù the gospel to fit the moment. She does not trade the cross for spectacle.

And Scripture is explicit: counterfeit power can ride on counterfeit signs (2 Thessalonians 2:9‚Äì10). Therefore discernment is obedience, not cynicism‚Äîtesting everything by the Word, keeping Christ central.

Anchor Protocol: the Word is final; the cross is central.

---

6) Marked by Love: Heat in a Cold World

Jesus said love would grow cold (Matthew 24:12). That means love becomes a battlefield. The church‚Äôs signature under pressure is not outrage. It is holy, disciplined love.

Jesus makes it the identifying mark: ‚ÄúBy this all people will know that you are My disciples, if you have love for one another‚Äù (John 13:35). Love is not theater. Love is obedience with sacrifice attached‚Äîlove for God, love for the saints, love for enemies (Deuteronomy 6:5; John 13:34‚Äì35; Matthew 5:44).

Love Protocol: warm heart, clean hands, steel spine.

---

Corporate Readiness: The Church as a Unit

Readiness is not a solo sport. Hebrews commands the church to stir one another up and to gather‚Äî‚Äúand all the more as you see the Day drawing near‚Äù (Hebrews 10:24‚Äì25). And Revelation‚Äôs lampstand warnings are addressed to churches (Revelation 2‚Äì3). Christ holds congregations accountable for doctrine, compromise, endurance, and love.

Return-ready believers build return-ready churches: gathering, repenting, correcting doctrine, restoring love, and holding the line together.

---

Field Drills: Turn Doctrine Into Muscle Memory

Use these as weekly drills‚Äîsimple, measurable, repeatable:

Awake: Daily Berean check‚Äîone claim tested by Scripture (Acts 17:11).

Clean: Confess one sin; cut one access point this week (1 John 1:9).

Courageous: Obey one command you‚Äôve been delaying (James 1:22).

Mission: Share Christ once; disciple one person once (Matthew 28:18‚Äì20).

Anchored: Identify one false teaching trend; answer with the Word (2 Timothy 4:3‚Äì4).

Love: Pray for one enemy; take one reconciliation step (Matthew 5:44).

No performance. No posturing. Just faithfulness.

---

Snapshot: What Christ Should Find When He Returns

A return-ready church looks like this:

Lamps burning‚Äîoil in the vessel, not just light on the stage (Matthew 25:1‚Äì13).

Hands on the plow‚Äîno backward drift (Luke 9:62).

Armor on‚Äîtruth, righteousness, gospel readiness, faith, salvation, the Word, prayer (Ephesians 6:10‚Äì18).

A bride preparing‚Äîpurity, repentance, loyalty (Revelation 19:7‚Äì8).

A body building‚Äîgathered, exhorting, strengthening (Hebrews 10:24‚Äì25).

A witness standing‚ÄîSpirit-empowered testimony (Acts 1:8).

Not perfect, but awake. Not sinless, but repentant. Not loud, but faithful.

---

Altar Call: Come Home Before the Trumpet

If Christ returned tonight, you don‚Äôt want to meet Him holding excuses. You want to meet Him holding faith.

If you know you‚Äôre not right with God‚Äîif you‚Äôve drifted, if you‚Äôve been playing games, if sin has you chained, or if you‚Äôve never surrendered‚Äîthis is your moment. Jesus Christ died for sinners and rose again. He saves by grace, and He makes people ready.

Pray this‚Äîplain, honest, no performance:

Lord Jesus, I confess I am a sinner. I cannot save myself. I believe You died for my sins and rose again. I turn from my sin and surrender to You as Lord. Save me, cleanse me, and make me ready for Your return. In Jesus‚Äô name, amen.

I wanted to say a few words about @Tesla and @elonmusk regarding their decision, announced during yesterday's earnings call, to end the production of the Model S and X in Q2 this year.  

From the start, I have been a giant fan, investor and supporter of Tesla.  I was the happy purchaser of the 2008 Roadster and 2012 Model S, both VIN #003.  I continue to hold them in pristine condition until one day they go into either the (hopeful!) Tesla Museum or another tech or automotive museum.  I still drive my 2010 Roadster and I have owned a number of Model S's and Model X's over the years.  

As I once told Elon, the Model S (Motortrend's Car of the Year for 2012) goes alongside the PC, Mac, iPad and iPhone as the greatest consumer tech products ever created, in my opinion.  

I recently upgraded my personal, older Tesla's with 2026 Model S's (Plaid and Long Range) and a 2026 Model X Plaid.  They are all the best cars I have ever owned.  I did this even knowing that the writing was on the wall that they would be discontinued as the sales numbers were a rounding error compared to the Model 3 and Y.  I did buy a 2026 Model Y as well when it came out...it is an excellent car and at the price, a very good value. 

Over the years, I also subsidized employees across my various organizations with a $7500 credit towards the purchase of a Tesla...and that was on top of the Federal EV credits when they existed.  I am proud to have introduced 100s of people to owning Tesla vehicles, especially in the early days when the sales mattered.  

While I will miss future versions of the S and X, I have no doubt that Tesla will continue to make great cars and the FSD is now amazing, so I have little doubt that whatever package the FSD is wrapped inside, it will be a great experience.  

Elon always said that Tesla was intended to be more than a car company and today it is already a major player in renewable energy, manufacturing, software and well on its way to being a winner in robotics and whatever future areas of tech hold the most promise.   

So farewell to the Model S and X, with gratitude for the many years of enjoyment and hello to the future!
